'''Tatsuo Murayama''' (1915 - 2010) was a Japanese politician who was a member of [[Liberal Democratic Party (Japan)|the Liberal Democratic Party (LDP)]] and finance minister for two times.

==Early life==
Tatsuo Murayama was born in 1910.<ref name=rulers>{{cite web|title=Japanese ministers|url=http://rulers.org/japgov.html|publisher=Rulers|accessdate=8 January 2013}}</ref> 

==Career==
Murayama was part of the faction headed by [[Kiichi Miyazawa]] in the LDP.<ref name=nstimes/> 

Murayama served as finance minister twice. Murayama replaced Hideo Bo as finance minister on 28 November 1977. Murayama's successor was Ippei Kaneko who was appointed on 8 December 1978.<ref name=rulers/> The second term of Murayama was from 27 December 1988 to 9 August 1989 in the cabinet of then prime minister [[Noboru Takeshita]].<ref name=nstimes>{{cite news|title=Murayama is new finance minister|url=http://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1309&dat=19881227&id=2IJUAAAAIBAJ&sjid=NZADAAAAIBAJ&pg=7073,2901452|accessdate=8 January 2013|newspaper=New Straits Times|date=27 December 1988}}</ref> He replaced Noboru Takeshita, who had served as acting finance minister since the resignation of Kiichi Miyazawa due to his alleged involvement in [[Recruit scandal|the Recruit stock scandal]] on 9 December 1988.<ref name=nstimes/><ref name=karl>{{cite news|last=Schoenberger|first=Karl|title=Takeshita Shuffles Cabinet but Retains Key Ministers|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1988-12-28/news/mn-929_1_prime-minister|accessdate=8 January 2013|newspaper=Los Angeles Times|date=28 December 1988|location=Tokyo}}</ref> On 9 August 1989, late Ryutaro Hashimoto replaced Murayama as finance minister.<ref name=rulers/> 

